	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />When testing for defects in the parts of a program that do I/O (usually the video or sound code), I care about accuracy because my program is unknown.
<br />
<br />But once I know a program's I/O is solid, I start testing for game logic defects or balance. At that point, I start to care more about ways I can sacrifice accuracy in obscure cases to gain speed accuracy while retaining compatibility. When play-testing things on the city bus, I'll even turn on PocketNES's PPU hack and auto speed hack (e.g. BEQ skipping or BVC skipping) because it makes the speed more accurate.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
